Achieving Open/Closed Principle with Controllers
Controllers should remain closed for modifications even when new functionality is required. This can be achieved by using interfaces for interacting with controllers. While adhering strictly to the Open/Closed Principle (OCP) can be challenging in real scenarios, using abstractions and interfaces can help minimize dependencies.
// Interface or abstraction for a controller
public interface Controller {
    void processInput();
}

// Concrete implementation of a controller
public class ConcreteController implements Controller {
    public void processInput() {
        // Input processing
        // ...
    }
}

// Adding new functionality to the controller without changing existing code
public class ExtendedController implements Controller {
    public void processInput() {
        // Input processing
        // ...new functionality...
    }
}
